&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Sex Education Forum [OLS0070][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Summary[bold]1. Technical solutions such as lessons about online s
[normal]afety in computing classes and internet controls are by themselves insufficient to protect children and young people. A broad and comprehensive programme of sex and relationships education (SRE) in school is essential to ensure that children and young peop
[normal]le get accurate information about sex and sexual health and an understanding of what constitutes respectful relationships.  This has been recognised in numerous reports including by 
[normal]Ofsted
[normal] and the Office of the Children’s Commissioner. 
[normal]2. A broad programm
[normal]e of good quality SRE should also address the issue of on-line safety and pornography. This can complement the more technical learning about safety gained through computing classes. 
[normal]3. Currently the provision of SRE in schools is unacceptably patchy and i
[normal]nconsistent.
[normal] 
[normal]Every child and young person has a right to comprehensive SRE and we (as adults) have a duty to ensure this.  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4. 
[normal]The best way to ensure this is by making SRE (within Personal, Social, Health and Economic (PSHE) education) 
[normal]compulsory
[normal] for prim
[normal]ary and secondary schools, and for teachers to receive training on the subject. 
[normal]The Government guidance on SRE should also be updated to provide clarity to schools.  
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. The majority of parents want SRE to be compulsory in schools and many would also li
[normal]ke support to fulfil their role at home as educators about growing up, safety, sex and relationships.
[normal]6. Our evidence submission to this inquiry covers: 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]What is SRE and how can it address online safety?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]7. SRE involves learning about the emotional, social and physical aspects of growing up, relationships, human sexuality, sex and sexual health. It should equip children and young people with the information, skills and positive values to enable them to hav
[normal]e safe, fulfilling relationships and to take responsibility for their sexual health and wellbeing. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8. 
[normal]Children and young people sometimes find pornography 
[normal]because they are looking for information about sex and relationships online
[normal]. 
[normal]Further research is 
[normal]needed to establish if there is a link between good quality SRE and access/avoidance of pornography. Gaps in research about the link between accessing pornography and behaviour are identified by Horvath (2013) in the Office of the 
[normal]Chidlren’s
[normal] Commissioner 
[normal]r
[normal]eport
[normal] ‘Basically...porn is everywhere’. However, p
[normal]rovision of good quality SRE means that young people 
[normal]have a reliable source of information about sex and 
[normal]relationships.
[normal] 
[normal]Good quality 
[normal]SRE 
[normal]contributes to understanding
[normal] how pornography distorts reality 
[normal]by disc
[normal]ussing how
[normal] media represent
[normal]s
[normal] men and women and gender roles, and how pictures and videos are routinely edited. 
[normal]9. The Sex Education Forum e-magazine shows how pornography and issues related to it can be effectively addressed in SRE and includes suggestions
[normal] from pupils about the key messages that should be taught to their peers. 
[normal]10.
[normal] [bold]This is what a group of Year 11 pupils thought other young people should know about pornography:
[normal] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About safety[bold]: Not all things shown in pornography are safe in your own sex li
[normal]fe: keep safe, use condoms and go to a clinic regularly. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About privacy[bold]: No video cameras in the room! In case you film yourself but then have a bad breakup, keep your sex life private. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About reality[bold]: Don't believe everything you see. Pornography is act
[normal]ing and not 'real'. The sex and bodies are mostly unrealistic - and there is a lot of editing. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About the actors[bold]: Some people may be forced into making it. Some actors use performance enhancing drugs to 'perform' or to be able to get through stuff that is
[normal] painful. It can affect the actors physically, mentally and emotionally, and can mean that relationships suffer. There are dangers risked by the actors like infections and abuse. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]About sex lives and relationships[bold]: You can learn some helpful positions from some films. The so-called pleasure you see may be anything but. You don't have to watch it at all. It can be addictive to the viewer and can mean that you might not be able to have a healthy, happy sex life yours
[normal]elf if you are addicted. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Always [bold]have[bold] consent[bold]: don't pressure people to do stuff from pornography or to watch it if they don't want to.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]From ‘The Sex Educational Supplement’ Issue 1 (2013).
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11. 
[normal]At primary school classes should start with discussing diff
[normal]erences between boys and girls bodies, and the importance of loving and respectful relationships. Learning correct names for genitalia is important so that children have the language to describe their bodies, understand what behaviour would be abusive and 
[normal]report it if it happens to them. At secondary level lessons can look at ‘
[normal]sexting
[normal]’ and pressures from peers and make more direct reference to pornography in the context of learning about consent, body image, gender roles and respectful relationships. 
[normal]12. H
[normal]aving a basic universal language about respect, our bodies, growing up and sex is essential to support children with the words needed to report abuse and the belief that it is ‘OK to talk about this’.  
[normal]What is the standard of SRE in schools today?[bold]13
[normal].Ofsted
[normal] inspectors report that SRE is currently inadequate in a third of schools (2013).
[normal] Young people have repeatedly said that the SRE they receive is inadequate – with 28% describing their school SRE as ‘bad’ or ‘very bad’ in a survey in 2011 (Sex Educ
[normal]ation Forum). Young people say that the relationships aspect of SRE is the most neglected
[normal] (Sex Education Forum 2008)
[normal].
[normal] [bold]14. 
[normal]Ofsted
[normal] 
[normal]consulted pupils for their recent PSHE report ‘Not yet good enough’ (2013) and consequently 
[normal]recommended that schools address p
[normal]ornography within SRE
[normal]. New research with young people carried out by Brook (2013 unpublished: also being submitted to this inquiry) shows that young people want 
[normal]young people need better, more inclusive education on internet safety, both for children and fo
[normal]r parents, 
[normal]not least 
[normal]to ensure that knowledge, skills and understanding around online safety are embedded in the next generati
[normal]on. 
[normal]15. 
[normal]Ofsted
[normal] are also concerned that some primary schools are failing to teach the basic body science that is necessary to unde
[normal]rpin further learning about bodily privacy and safety. They found: “
[normal]younger pupils had not always learnt the correct names for sexual body parts
[normal]” and see this as a safeguarding failure because it leaves children without the language skills to understand th
[normal]eir bodies, know what is acceptable / unacceptable and to say what has happened to them (2013).
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]What is the evidence that SRE works? [bold]&#xa0;[bold]16. National and international research shows that good quality SRE has a protective function as young people who have good SRE are more likely to choose to have sex for the first time later, more likely to use contraception and to have fewer sexual partne
[normal]rs (Kirby 2007, UNESCO 2009 and NICE 2010). 
[normal]17. A comprehensive 
[normal]programme
[normal] of SRE also results in young people being less likely to have an ‘age-discrepant’ partner (Lindberg 2012). 
[normal]Having an older partner is a significant risk factor for experiencing phys
[normal]ical, emotional and sexual violence (for girls) – and a risk for sexual exploitation
[normal] (Barter, 2009). 
[normal]18. There is also evidence that SRE is more effective if home and school are involved (Kirby 2007 and see 
[normal]Emmerson
[normal] 2011). Parents are overwhelmingly suppo
[normal]rtive of SRE and a recent survey shows that 83% of parents want SRE lessons to cover issues relating to pornography (NAHT, 2013 and see also 
[normal]Mumsnet
[normal] 2011).  
[normal]19. SRE aims to contribute to behavior change, including reducing unprotected and unwanted sex, an
[normal]d reducing harmful 
[normal]behaviour
[normal], including sexual offences such as assault and abuse. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20. Good SRE, together with access to sexual health services will contribute to several public health priorities that are essential for the health and well-being of the na
[normal]tion, and especially to women:  
